      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Key Observations\n\n- **Stepwise constants (K)** dominate the database, accounting for over three-quarters of all measurements. This reflects the common experimental practice of reporting equilibrium constants for successive ligand-binding steps (M + L ⇌ ML, ML + L ⇌ ML₂, etc.).\n- **Hydrolysis constants (H)** make up ~12% of entries, capturing the important chemistry of metal-ion hydrolysis in aqueous solution — a critical factor in environmental and biological speciation.\n- **Overall (cumulative) stability constants (S/β)** represent ~11% of the data. These describe the global formation reaction (M + nL ⇌ MLₙ) and are especially useful for thermodynamic modeling and speciation calculations.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
